SIMPLE: incumbency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incumbency
<hw>In*cum"ben*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Incumbencies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[From
<er>Incumbent</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being incumbent; a lying or resting on
something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is physically incumbent; that which lies
as a burden; a weight.</def> <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is morally incumbent, or is imposed, as a
rule, a duty, obligation, or responsibility.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>incumbencies</xex> of a family.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Donne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The state of holding a benefice; the full possession
and exercise of any office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These fines are only to be paid to the bishop during his
<qex>incumbency</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incumbent</ent>⟦br⟧
